{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7ea23a63-5a59-438e-a225-37c0c3acc956","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK went up → workloads need to go up too → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf issues persist after updating, also try:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build --no-incremental\n```\n\nThe `--no-incremental` flag forces a clean rebuild, clearing any stale cached artifacts from the old SDK.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"49ba5f54-7702-42c5-97bf-916aff2c5559","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any code or run any commands.","outputTokens":270,"requestId":"3C21:16C73:D34A8B:10710F2:6A0128FD"},"id":"c426a7f7-5e83-4b60-8c4b-35583172035c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:55:33.066Z","parentId":"c896d080-ba76-46f9-9181-00a1ea5cc00e"}
